Trump and economics
New York—Financial markets have finally woken up, it turns out Trump is the U.S. president.
The world has tolerated this person with the most power globally for over two years of unchecked Twitter and public comments, and it's clear: what's keeping it going?
On the one hand, until now, investors have only seen Trump waving his umbrella without raining.
As long as he adopts tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies beneficial to corporate departments and shareholders, they would be willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that in the end, "the adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies stay on track.
This assumption was largely confirmed in Trump's first year in office, during which economic growth and profit expectations for companies increased — fueled by the impending tax cuts and deregulation — which made the stock market shine.
In 2017, the U.S. stock index rose more than 20%.
However, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, especially in the last few months of 2018.
Although the company's profit increased more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market has been fluctuating for most of the year and is now plummeting.
Currently, all indices are located in the correction range (i.e., the latest high fell by 10%), and the technology stock index (such as Nasdaq) has fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Despite the increased volatility in the financial markets, which reflects concerns over China, Italy and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of this year, Trump implemented a reckless tax cut, which resulted in a surge in long-term interest rates, pushing the economy, which was already close to full employment, to a peak.
Concerns over inflation rising above the Fed's 2% target led to the first wave of risk aversion in 2018 by February.
Subsequently, Trump launched trade wars with China and other important US trading partners.
Concerns about government protectionism policies have ebbed and flowed over the course of a year, but are now reaching a new high.
The United States' recent actions towards China seem to be preparing for an all-encompassing trade, economic, and geo-political cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation, a situation where economic growth slows down while inflation rises.
Ultimately, Trump was prepared to restrict foreign direct investment inflows and implemented a broader range of immigration restrictions, which would have slowed the growth of labor supply in a situation where the aging labor force and skill mismatch are becoming increasingly serious.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy through infrastructure.
Trump has repeatedly attacked companies' hiring, production, investment and pricing behaviors in Twitter and elsewhere, especially in the tech industry, which faces widespread opposition and increasingly intense competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets were also hit by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening pushed up both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the US dollar.
As a result, emerging economies faced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries that only have indirect trade relations with China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The US reinstatement of sanctions on Iran drove up oil prices, and subsequently, the US administration cancelled the exemption, threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, resulting in a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although US consumers benefit from low oil prices, US energy companies' stocks cannot hold up.
Beyond this, excessive fluctuations in oil prices are detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hampers wise investment and consumption decisions.
What's worse is that now, it's apparent that almost all the benefits of last year's tax cuts have flowed to corporate departments, rather than to households in the form of genuinely higher wages after adjusting for inflation.
This suggests that household consumption may slow down soon, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in the U.S. and global stock markets was Trump's own statements and actions.
Worse still is Trump's public attacks on the Federal Reserve, which began in the spring of 2018, when the US economic growth rate was above 4 %.
Thanks to those earlier criticisms, the market became a scared bird after the Fed made the right decision to raise interest rates this month and hinted at a slower pace of rate hikes in 2019.
More likely, the Fed's relatively hawkish stance is a reaction to Trump's attacks on it.
In the face of tweets from the president with hostile intent, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains its political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to allocate funding for the useless Mexican border wall, Trump decided to let the federal government partially shut down.
This move sent the market into a quasi-panic state, and with the government shut down, reports quickly emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could send the market correction into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump did not have a plan to fire Powell, the US financial situation is good, but this exactly highlights the question of whether the situation is really good.
Recent government internal personnel changes may also worry the market and will not necessarily affect economic decision-making.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are both set to resign, leaving Trump's Cabinet with no one of sound judgment.
The rest will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, with Trump as the leader.
The possibility of a full-scale conflict over Taiwan with China cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War is highly likely to lead to globalization, disrupt global supply chains, and the technology industry will be the first to suffer, with the recent cases of Huawei and ZTE serving as evidence.
At the same time, Trump seems to be determined to undermine the cohesion of the European Union and NATO at a time when Europe's economy and politics are unstable.
Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign ties with Russia has been the Sword of Damocles hanging over Trump's presidency.
Donald Trump is now the financial markets' Dr. Love.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in an irretrievable economic ruin from mutual destruction.
Today, the market sees this risk, the risk of a financial crisis and a global recession is rising steadily.
